### **Step 2.3: Relative Value Analysis**

Always compare similar stocks to find mispricings:

```
PAIRS COMPARISON TEMPLATE:

Stock A vs Stock B (Same sector, similar business model):

VALUATION METRICS:
â”œâ”€ P/E: Stock A at 12Ã—, Stock B at 15Ã— (B expensive 25%)
â”œâ”€ P/B: Stock A at 1.8Ã—, Stock B at 2.2Ã— (B expensive 22%)
â”œâ”€ EV/EBITDA: Stock A at 7Ã—, Stock B at 9Ã— (B expensive 29%)
â”œâ”€ Dividend Yield: Stock A 4.5%, Stock B 3.2% (A yields 140bp more)
â””â”€ Average Premium: Stock B trades 25% richer

FUNDAMENTAL JUSTIFICATION:
Does Stock B deserve premium?
â”œâ”€ Growth: B growing 15%/yr vs A at 10% = Justified 5-10% premium
â”œâ”€ ROIC: B at 22% vs A at 18% = Justified 5-10% premium
â”œâ”€ Balance Sheet: Similar leverage = No premium justified
â”œâ”€ Management: B has better track record = Justified 5% premium
â””â”€ Total Justified Premium: 15-25%

VERDICT:
â”œâ”€ Actual Premium: 25%
â”œâ”€ Justified Premium: 15-25%
â”œâ”€ Mispricing: FAIR TO SLIGHT OVERVAL

UE (B at high end)

TRADE IDEAS:
1. If B premium >30%: Long A, Short B (pairs trade)
2. If A discount >20%: Long A only (relative value)
3. If both cheap vs sector: Long both (sector bet)
â””â”€ Best Risk/Reward: Option 2 (long A at discount)

CATALYST FOR CONVERGENCE:
â”œâ”€ Stock A announces turnaround plan
â”œâ”€ Stock B disappoints on earnings
â”œâ”€ Sector rotation brings value focus
â””â”€ Expected timeframe: 3-6 months
```

