## **PHASE 3: PROBABILISTIC POSITION SIZING**
*"Kelly Criterion, expected value, risk-adjusted returns"*

### **Step 3.1: Scenario Analysis & Expected Value**

For EVERY high-conviction stock (score â‰¥7.5), run scenario analysis:

```
THREE-SCENARIO FRAMEWORK:

BULL CASE (Probability: X%):
â”œâ”€ Trigger: [What has to happen]
â”œâ”€ Price Target: IDR [Y,YYY]
â”œâ”€ Upside: +ZZ%
â”œâ”€ Timeframe: [Days/weeks/months]
â””â”€ Key Assumptions: [1-3 critical factors]

BASE CASE (Probability: Y%):
â”œâ”€ Rationale: [Most likely path]
â”œâ”€ Price Target: IDR [Y,YYY]
â”œâ”€ Return: +/-ZZ%
â”œâ”€ Timeframe: [Days/weeks/months]
â””â”€ Key Assumptions: [1-3 critical factors]

BEAR CASE (Probability: Z%):
â”œâ”€ Trigger: [What goes wrong]
â”œâ”€ Price Target: IDR [Y,YYY]
â”œâ”€ Downside: -ZZ%
â”œâ”€ Timeframe: [Days/weeks/months]
â””â”€ Key Assumptions: [1-3 critical factors]

Probabilities must sum to 100%

EXPECTED VALUE CALCULATION:
EV = (P_bull Ã— R_bull) + (P_base Ã— R_base) + (P_bear Ã— R_bear)

Example - ANTM:
EV = (0.35 Ã— 16%) + (0.50 Ã— 9%) + (0.15 Ã— -8%)
   = 5.6% + 4.5% - 1.2%
   = 8.9% expected return

RISK METRICS:
Standard Deviation = âˆš[Î£ P_i Ã— (R_i - EV)Â²]
Sharpe Ratio = (EV - Risk-Free Rate) / Std Dev
Sortino Ratio = (EV - Risk-Free) / Downside Dev (only negative returns)

Use Sharpe >1.0 as minimum threshold for recommendations
```

### **Step 3.2: Kelly Criterion Position Sizing**

```
KELLY FORMULA:
f* = (bp - q) / b

Where:
â”œâ”€ f* = Optimal fraction of capital to allocate
â”œâ”€ b = Odds received (avg upside / avg downside ratio)
â”œâ”€ p = Probability of positive return (bull + base if base positive)
â”œâ”€ q = Probability of loss (1 - p)

CALCULATION EXAMPLE - ANTM:
p = 85% (bull 35% + base 50% both positive)
q = 15% (bear case)
Avg Upside = (35% Ã— 16% + 50% Ã— 9%) / 85% = 11.2%
Avg Downside = 8% (bear case)
b = 11.2% / 8% = 1.40

f* = (1.40 Ã— 0.85 - 0.15) / 1.40
   = (1.19 - 0.15) / 1.40
   = 74.3% (!!!)

PRACTICAL ADJUSTMENTS:
â”œâ”€ Full Kelly is too aggressive â†’ Use HALF KELLY: 74% / 2 = 37%
â”œâ”€ Portfolio diversification rule: Max 15% per position
â”œâ”€ Liquidity constraint: Tier 1 (>500B daily) = up to 10%, Tier 2 = up to 6%
â”œâ”€ Correlation adjustment: If >3 correlated positions, reduce each by 20%
â””â”€ FINAL ALLOCATION: 10% (balances all factors)

POSITION SIZING TABLE:
â”œâ”€ Confluence 9.0-10.0 + Sharpe >1.5: 8-10% allocation
â”œâ”€ Confluence 8.0-8.9 + Sharpe 1.0-1.5: 6-8% allocation
â”œâ”€ Confluence 7.0-7.9 + Sharpe 0.8-1.0: 4-6% allocation
â”œâ”€ Confluence 6.0-6.9 + Sharpe 0.5-0.8: 2-4% allocation
â”œâ”€ Confluence 5.0-5.9: 0-2% (avoid or watchlist)
â””â”€ Confluence <5.0: 0% (exclude)
```

### **Step 3.3: Portfolio-Level Risk Management**

Monitor these metrics DAILY:

```
PORTFOLIO RISK METRICS:

1. VALUE AT RISK (VaR):
   â”œâ”€ Definition: Maximum expected loss at 95% confidence over 1 day
   â”œâ”€ Calculation: Position size Ã— Volatility Ã— 1.65 (95% z-score)
   â”œâ”€ Example: 10% position Ã— 4% daily vol Ã— 1.65 = 0.66% portfolio loss
   â”œâ”€ Target: Portfolio VaR <3% (can lose max 3% in 1 day, 95% of time)
   â””â”€ Action if exceeded: Reduce position sizes or add hedges

2. CORRELATION MATRIX:
   â”œâ”€ Measure pairwise correlation of all positions
   â”œâ”€ High correlation (>0.7): Effective concentration risk
   â”œâ”€ Example: ANTM, MDKA, ADMR, ARCI all 0.85+ = like 1 giant position
   â”œâ”€ Target: No more than 40% in highly correlated positions (>0.7)
   â””â”€ Action: Diversify sectors OR add negatively correlated hedge

3. FACTOR EXPOSURES:
   â”œâ”€ Beta to IDX: Measure portfolio's market sensitivity
   â”œâ”€ Gold Beta: % exposure to gold price moves
   â”œâ”€ USD/IDR Beta: Currency sensitivity (exporters vs importers)
   â”œâ”€ Interest Rate Duration: Sensitivity to BI rate changes
   â”œâ”€ Target: Understand factor exposures, hedge if excessive (>70% to one factor)
   â””â”€ Example: 70% gold beta â†’ Consider shorting 20% gold ETF or gold miners

4. MAXIMUM DRAWDOWN:
   â”œâ”€ Individual Position: -8% stop loss (HARD RULE)
   â”œâ”€ Sector Exposure: If sector down >15%, reduce allocation by 50%
   â”œâ”€ Total Portfolio: If down >12% from peak, cut all risk by 50%
   â””â”€ Circuit Breaker: If down >20%, exit ALL positions and reassess

5. LIQUIDITY STRESS TEST:
   â”œâ”€ Question: Can we exit 50% of portfolio in 3 days with <3% slippage?
   â”œâ”€ Tier 1 stocks (>IDR 500B daily): Yes, minimal slippage
   â”œâ”€ Tier 2 stocks (50-500B daily): Possible but 1-2% slippage
   â”œâ”€ Tier 3 stocks (<50B daily): NO - illiquid, 5-10% slippage
   â”œâ”€ Target: >80% of portfolio in Tier 1+2 (liquid)
   â””â”€ Action: Limit Tier 3 to <15% of portfolio

6. CONCENTRATION LIMITS:
   â”œâ”€ Single stock: Maximum 15% (even ultra-high conviction)
   â”œâ”€ Single sector: Maximum 40% (even metals supercycle)
   â”œâ”€ Single country: Indonesia = 100% (accept home bias or diversify regionally)
   â”œâ”€ Single factor (gold, oil, rates): Maximum 60% exposure
   â””â”€ Cash minimum: Never <10% (dry powder + buffer)
```

---

## **PHASE 4: DYNAMIC HEDGING STRATEGIES**
*"Reduce risk without killing returns"*

### **Hedge Architecture**

```
FIVE HEDGE TYPES:

1. SECTOR HEDGES (Most common):
   Setup: Long 50% mining â†’ Short 15% coal stocks
   â”œâ”€ Rationale: Mining (metals) in supercycle, coal in structural decline
   â”œâ”€ Execution: Long ANTM, MDKA, TINS / Short PTBA, ADRO
   â”œâ”€ Net Exposure: 35% long commodities (hedged)
   â”œâ”€ Cost: Opportunity cost if coal rallies (low probability)
   â””â”€ Benefit: Protects if ALL commodities fall (only coal underperforms more)

2. PAIRS TRADES (Market neutral):
   Setup: Long undervalued / Short overvalued in SAME sector
   â”œâ”€ Example: Long MDKA (EV/EBITDA 6Ã—) / Short ANTM (EV/EBITDA 8.5Ã—)
   â”œâ”€ Bet: MDKA re-rates to ANTM multiple (relative value converges)
   â”œâ”€ Market neutral: If sector falls, both fall but spread narrows
   â”œâ”€ Execution: Dollar-neutral (equal IDR amount long and short)
   â””â”€ Benefit: Lower volatility, alpha from stock selection not market direction

3. FACTOR HEDGES (Cross-sector):
   Setup: Long cyclicals / Short defensives
   â”œâ”€ Example: Long ANTM (gold, cyclical) / Short INDF (consumer staples)
   â”œâ”€ Rationale: If recession hits, gold up (safe haven) but consumers down
   â”œâ”€ Net: Balanced exposure, profit from relative performance
   â””â”€ Use when: Macro uncertainty high but directional view on factors

4. TAIL RISK HEDGES (Insurance):
   Setup: Buy IDX put options (out-of-money)
   â”œâ”€ Strike: 10-15% below current IDX level
   â”œâ”€ Maturity: 3 months
   â”œâ”€ Cost: ~2-3% of portfolio (insurance premium)
   â”œâ”€ Payoff: If IDX crashes >15%, put gains offset long losses
   â””â”€ When to use: VIX equivalent >20, geopolitical stress, extreme valuations

5. CURRENCY HEDGES (For exporters):
   Setup: USD/IDR forward contracts
   â”œâ”€ Scenario: ANTM exports (USD revenues), portfolio in IDR
   â”œâ”€ Weak IDR = Good for ANTM stock (higher IDR revenues)
   â”œâ”€ But if managing USD-based wealth, need hedge
   â”œâ”€ Execution: Sell USD forward at current rate (lock in exchange rate)
   â””â”€ Size: Hedge 30-50% of expected USD flows

HEDGING PRINCIPLES:
â”œâ”€ Hedge what you can't afford to lose (size matters)
â”œâ”€ Hedge factors, not stocks (diversifiable risk = don't hedge)
â”œâ”€ Hedge costs money (opportunity cost or premium) - must be worth it
â”œâ”€ Rebalance hedges as exposures change
â””â”€ Remove hedges when risk subsides (don't over-hedge)
```

